        "\n",
        "### The Interpretability-Performance Frontier\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Assessing Representational Capacity vs. Mechanistic Transparency\n",
        "\n",
        "To evaluate deep architecture utility, we partition predictive capacity into two paradigms:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Deep Consensus ($\\mathbf{Y}|\\mathbf{U}$):** Predictor trained on the final, deep non-linear shared latent space. This represents the upper bound of representational capacity [@hornik1989multilayer; @goodfellow2016deep].\n",
        "2. **Strictly Linear ($\\mathbf{Y}|\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf{V}$):** Predictor trained only on the concatenated linear projections of the first layer ($[\\mathbf{X}_1 \\mathbf{V}_1, \\mathbf{X}_2 \\mathbf{V}_2]$). This isolates performance achieved through auditable pathways.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Linear-to-Deep Performance Parity\n",
        "\n",
        "Evaluation reveals that under optimized sparsity and orthogonality constraints, the **Strictly Linear Accuracy ($\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf{V}$)** maintains high performance, approaching parity with the deep consensus ($\\mathbf{U}$). This Linear-to-Deep Performance Parity proves the shared linear bottleneck extracts the fundamental feature variance. The deep layers in NED and NEDPP act as modular extensions to handle extreme manifold complexities or sequester view-specific noise, not as replacements for the auditable foundation. This architecture aligns with private-shared space paradigms for domain separation [@bousmalis2016domain].\n",
        "\n",
        "![**Figure 4: Linear-to-Deep Performance Parity (Real-World).** Baseline (Pure Deep Performance, $\\mathbf{Y}|\\mathbf{U}$) compared to the Proposed Auditable Performance ($\\mathbf{Y}|\\mathbf{X}\\mathbf{V}$). Points clustering along the dashed parity line indicate the linear basis captures the majority of the predictive signal. Parity allows for high-performance discovery where the linear entry point serves as an exact audit trail, eliminating the performance penalty typically associated with linear constraints.](figures/fig_v21_blessing_interpretability.png){#fig-v21-blessing-interpretability width=\"100%\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "| Factor | Effect Size ($\\eta^2_p$) [@cohen1973eta] | p-value (Synthetic) | p-value (Real) | Interpretation |\n",
        "| :--- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :--- |\n",
        "| **Model** | 0.24 | $< 10^{-8}$ | $< 10^{-8}$ | Architecture dominates ground-truth recovery. |\n",
        "| **Regime/Dataset** | 0.92 | $< 10^{-80}$ | $< 10^{-30}$ | Data topology is the primary variance driver. |\n",
        ": **Table 6: Analysis of Variance.** Breakdown of performance variance by model and regime. Data topology dictates difficulty, while the proposed architectures significantly drive ground-truth recovery. {#tbl-anova}\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Rigorous Statistical Review: Deep-to-Linear Benefit\n",
        "\n",
        "Comparing Deep models (LEND, NED, NEDPP) against the linear baseline (SiMLR), we quantify the 'Deep-to-Linear Benefit'. The proposed architectures deliver statistically significant improvements in strictly linear accuracy. In synthetic analyses (@tbl-stat-sig-synthetic), we observe large effect sizes (Cohen's $d > 0.8$) and highly significant $p$-values ($p < 0.05$) in non-linear regimes. In clinical data, we observe significant improvements for the **Heart dataset** ($p = 8 \\times 10^{-11}$) and the **Diabetes dataset** ($p = 3 \\times 10^{-4}$). These results confirm that deep non-linear components discover more robust linear bases than pure linear optimization. We actively center effect sizes alongside $p$-values to verify the practical magnitude of this benefit [@wasserstein2016asa; @cohen1988statistical]."
